  "nursesNote": "Staying on prescribed psychiatric medication is the main way to prevent relapse and rehospitalization, so the nurse teaches the patient not to stop the medication even when feeling better, because the medication is what keeps symptoms away. The nurse addresses common barriers to adherence: bothersome side effects, cost, poor insight or denial of illness, complex regimens, and substance use. Strategies include simplifying the regimen, considering a long-acting injectable (depot) form, managing side effects rather than ignoring them, and building trust. The nurse teaches the patient and family to recognize early warning signs of relapse (changes in sleep, social withdrawal, stopping medication, or returning symptoms) and to follow a relapse plan that includes who to call. Family support and consistent follow-up reinforce adherence.",
